    <li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-58999">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-58999" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-58999">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-58999">ChrisSoyars</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-58999" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-58999" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Not according to the documentation, though it is up to you whether or not you believe them.</p>
<p><a href="http://developer.android.com/google/gcm/adv.html" rel="nofollow">http://developer.android.com/google/gcm/adv.html</a></p>
<p>&#8220;Otherwise, it will be stored in the GCM servers until the device is awake.&#8221;</p>
<p>&#8220;There is a limit on how many messages can be stored without collapsing. That limit is currently 100. If the limit is reached, all stored messages are discarded. Then when the device is back online, it receives a special message indicating that the limit was reached. The application can then handle the situation properly, typically by requesting a full sync.&#8221;</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li>
    <li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-59000">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-59000" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-59000">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-59000">ChrisSoyars</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-59000" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-59000" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Most of your questions are answered in the post by Open WhisperSystems (<a href="https://whispersystems.org/blog/cyanogen-integration/" rel="nofollow">https://whispersystems.org/blog/cyanogen-integration/</a>).</p>
<p>PFS: Forward secrecy is accomplished using the Axolotl forward secrecy ratchet (<a href="https://www.whispersystems.org/blog/advanced-ratcheting/" rel="nofollow">https://www.whispersystems.org/blog/advanced-ratcheting/</a>).</p>
<p>Are keys generated locally: Yes, of course.</p>
<p>Encryption algorithm used to generate keys: There are a few different keys in use.  The primitives are Curve25519, AES-256 and HmacSHA256.</p>
<p>What PRNG: Android&#8217;s SecureRandom (SHA1PRNG).  CyanogenMod 10.2&#8242;s PRNG is patched (<a href="http://review.cyanogenmod.org/#/c/49736/" rel="nofollow">http://review.cyanogenmod.org/#/c/49736/</a>)</p>
<p>I suggest reading the Open WhisperSystems post for a full explanation.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li>
