    <li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-59042">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-59042" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-59042">
https://www.n0t.net                <span id="dsq-author-user-59042">Axel Taferner</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-59042" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-59042" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>If you did read the blog post and comments, and did understand it, you would know a few things:</p>
<p>1) Your contacts or address book is NOT getting sent over the net to &#8220;some server&#8221;.<br />
2) You can verify this, because the code used to accomplish all this is open source. That means the source code to this is available to anyone, including you, to verify how and what exactly is being done. Trust is not required because you can verify it on your own.</p>
<p>The point is, you don&#8217;t have to rely on CM or any third party with this. because you can check the code and verify for yourself that what is being done makes it impossible for CM, a third party or the NSA to read your encrypted texts. If you can&#8217;t read the code yourself, perhaps someone you do trust can do it for you.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li>
    <li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-59043">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-59043" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-59043">
http://carbonize.co.uk/                <span id="dsq-author-user-59043">Carbonize</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-59043" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-59043" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>I&#8217;m sure all those people who got arrested after arranging to get together to rob shops during the London riots using BBM will be glad to know they can use this and not have to worry about it being stored on servers.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li>
    <li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-59045">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-59045" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-59045">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-59045">Stephan</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-59045" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-59045" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>I really appreciate your effort in term of CM in general.</p>
<p>But THIS could also have ben poste don April 1st&#8230;<br />
Due to the fact that you implemented a SILENT AUTOMATIC fallback to unencrypted messages you could&#8217;ve saved your breath for something more useful.</p>
<p>Please explain where in gods name the point of encryption is if it is pretty much &#8220;randomly and incontrolable&#8221; applied, or well&#8230; not.</p>
<p>THIS is not security done right.<br />
This implementation is just all wrong.</p>
<p>Just to put it straight:</p>
<p>One either wants secure messages, or not. There is no case ever to be where &#8220;security when you&#8217;re lucky&#8221; would make any sense.</p>
<p>IMO the whole concept is this implementation is a massive missconception.</p>
<p>PS: If this felt too rude, I&#8217;m sorry.</p>
<p>PPS: I am not saying, that this could not be improved to become actually useful but at the current state/concept it&#8217;s a waste of space in the rom.</p>
</div>
