    <li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-59047">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-59047" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-59047">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-59047">W. S.</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-59047" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-59047" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Comment#1156475563:<br />
&#8220;If I&#8217;m understanding this correctly, during registration the client sends hashes of the user&#8217;s entire address book to the server? So, someone who compromises the server can easily compute hashes of all possible phone numbers in a geographical region and they&#8217;ll get the entire social graph of all TextSecure and CM users in that region who register post-compromise. (I&#8217;m assuming the non-compromised server isn&#8217;t storing these hashed contact lists as it has no reason to.)</p>
<p>They&#8217;ll also get a large partial graph of non-users (eg, if Alice&#8217;s doesn&#8217;t use CM or TS but Bob and Carol do, the server learns whether Alice is a contact of Bob and/or Carol). Is this correct?&#8221;</p>
<p>Answer: &#8220;Your analysis is correct&#8230;&#8221; and &#8220;Yes, we are well aware that the preimage space of all possible phone numbers isn&#8217;t large enough for the hash to provide meaningful protection. We are hashing contacts because in the future, we will add other identifiers.&#8221;<br />
Enough for me.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li>
