    <li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-59052">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-59052" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-59052">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-59052">canadidan</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-59052" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-59052" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>I am excited to see all these innovations in personal privacy. Bringing secure voice and text communication to end users is important, and also presents an interesting challenge in making it accessible.</p>
<p>Unfortunately, I do not feel this integrated TextSecure middleware does the trick. It is little more than any other data based messaging platform, with encryption and integration improved upon. It still requires registering your number with the service. There are still privacy concerns with information, including metadata, passing through yet other servers. And it is no longer SMS, as it is completely carrier independent. It is in a tricky situation, like all other SMS replacement apps, as it shows that carrier SMS packages are no longer relevant.</p>
<p>The scene is spread thin with so many messaging alternatives and no standardization. SMS has not evolved in any way obvious to users for a long time, and perhaps what we need is not just another alt-messenger, but to rethink existing messaging platforms and create one with security and privacy as requirements, a new global standard. That&#8217;s being too optimistic, isn&#8217;t it.</p>
<p>I don&#8217;t mean to demean the genius of the middle ware layer that seamlessly deals with the encryption. This is great work. However I won&#8217;t be using thus service because I don&#8217;t feel it is the right solution.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li>
            </ul>

